"""
pasla - Secure ephemeral file-sharing server.

Serves a single file (or directory, auto-archived as tar) over HTTP/HTTPS with a
time-limited, token-protected URL.  Supports resumable downloads (HTTP Range),
SHA-256 integrity verification, and is hardened against common attack vectors.

Compatibility : Python 3.9+  (free-threaded: Python 3.13t+, recommended: 3.14t)
Dependencies  : none (standard library only; openssl CLI required for --https)

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
USAGE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Start (foreground):
    pasla <file> [duration_minutes] [max_downloads] [options]

  Start (background / detached):
    pasla -d <file> [duration_minutes] [max_downloads] [options]

  List active instances:
    pasla list

  Stop a specific instance:
    pasla stop <id>

  Stop all instances:
    pasla stop --all

OPTIONS
  -p, --port PORT   Bind to a specific port (default: random 40000-50000).
  -d, --detach      Run server in background; print URL then exit.
  -4, --ipv4        Use IPv4 only.
  -6, --ipv6        Use IPv6 only.
  --trust-proxy     Read client IP from X-Forwarded-For header.
                    Enable only when running behind a trusted reverse proxy
                    (Nginx, Cloudflare, etc.).  Never use on a server that
                    is directly internet-facing - a spoofed header would
                    bypass all IP-based controls.
  --single          Equivalent to max_downloads=1 (single-use link).
  --json            Print machine-readable JSON to stdout, suppress TUI.
  --allow-ip CIDR   Restrict downloads to specific IP/CIDR ranges. Repeatable.
  --https           Enable TLS.  Without --tls-cert/--tls-key, an ephemeral
                    self-signed ECDSA certificate is generated and removed on
                    shutdown (requires openssl CLI on PATH).  Uses TLS 1.3
                    when available, falls back to TLS 1.2 with secure ciphers
                    only.  Implied automatically when a usable TLS cert/key
                    pair is supplied via CLI or the [tls] config section.
  --no-https        Force plaintext HTTP even if the configuration would
                    otherwise enable HTTPS.
  --tls-cert PATH   Use an existing PEM certificate (or fullchain) at PATH
                    instead of generating an ephemeral one.  Use with
                    --tls-key.  PASLA_TLS_KEY_PASSWORD env var holds the
                    passphrase if the key is encrypted.
  --tls-key PATH    Path to the matching PEM private key for --tls-cert.
  --checksum        Force SHA-256 checksum computation.  Default: auto-enabled
                    for files <= 1 GB, disabled for larger files.  The hash is
                    shown in the startup banner and sent as a Digest header
                    (RFC 9530) in HTTP responses.
  --no-checksum     Disable SHA-256 checksum even for small files.
  --dry-run         Validate arguments, resolve IPs, print URL/JSON, then exit
                    without starting the server.  Useful for automation scripts.

EXAMPLES
  pasla report.zip
  pasla report.zip 30
  pasla report.zip 30 3 -d
  pasla -p 8080 report.zip
  pasla report.zip 60 --trust-proxy
  pasla report.zip --https --checksum
  pasla report.zip --json --dry-run
  pasla list
  pasla stop a1b2c3
  pasla stop --all

CONFIG FILE
  An optional INI config file provides default values for CLI arguments.
  The config file is never created or modified by pasla - read-only.

  Location:
    POSIX:   ~/.config/pasla
    Windows: %USERPROFILE%\\.pasla
    Override: PASLA_CONFIG environment variable

  Example:
    [server]
    duration = 30
    max_downloads = 5
    port = 8080

    [security]
    trust_proxy = false

    [tls]
    https = false
    # Optional: when both keys point to readable PEM files, HTTPS is
    # auto-enabled and pasla uses these credentials directly.
    # cert = /etc/letsencrypt/live/share.example.com/fullchain.pem
    # key  = /etc/letsencrypt/live/share.example.com/privkey.pem

  Priority: CLI argument > environment variable > config file > default

FREE-THREADED MODE (Python 3.13t+)
  python3.13t pasla report.pdf

SECTIONS (search by ruler)
  Configuration ................. constants and tuning knobs
  Threading HTTP server ......... ThreadingHTTPServer, process_request
  CLI argument parsing .......... argparse, parse_and_validate
  Config file support ........... _config_path, _load_config
  SHA-256 checksum .............. _compute_file_hash
  HTTPS cert generation ......... _generate_ephemeral_cert
  OSC 8 hyperlink ............... _osc8_link (clickable URLs)
  Registry management ........... instance lifecycle on disk
  Control plane ................. IPC via localhost TCP/JSON
  Security: rate limiting ....... bans, quotas, connection caps
  Transfer state machine ........ slot reservation, download counting
  Background maintenance ........ reaper, _cleanup_state, maintenance loop
  Request handler ............... make_handler → SecureHandler
  IP resolution ................. detect_public_ips, format_url
  Formatting helpers ............ _fmt_bytes, _fmt_remaining
  Live TUI ...................... _StatusBar, _LiveLogHandler
  Subcommands ................... list, stop, detach
  Main server startup ........... cmd_serve
